class Solution {
public:
    long long validSubstringCount(string word1, string word2) {
        int n = word1.size(), m = word2.size();
        long long count = 0;
        unordered_map<char, int> word1Count, word2Count;

        for (char c : word2) {
            word2Count[c]++;
        }

        int j = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            word1Count[word1[i]]++;
            while (j < i) {
                word1Count[word1[j]]--;
                if (word1Count[word1[j]] < word2Count[word1[j]]) {
                    break;
                }
                j++;
            }
            if (j == i && word1Count == word2Count) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(m)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses a sliding window approach with two pointers, i and j. It maintains a frequency count of characters in both word1 and word2. It expands the window to the right by incrementing the frequency count of the current character in word1 and contracts the window from the left by decrementing the frequency count of the character at the left boundary. If the frequency counts of word1 and word2 are equal at any point, it increments the count of valid substrings. This approach ensures a linear runtime complexity.

